    <fr:title text="First-order optimality condition">First-order optimality condition</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x_\star }]]></fr:tex> is a local minimizer of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f:\mathbb {R}^n\to \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is continuously differentiable in an open neighborhood of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x_\star }]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x_\star }]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="/003P/" title="Stationary point" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/003P/" display-uri="003P" type="local">stationary point</fr:link>:
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\nabla  f(\mathbf {x_\star })\ =\ \mathbf {0}.]]></fr:tex></html:p>
    <html:p>This is only <html:em>necessary</html:em>: a stationary point may be a maximizer or saddle, which is what the <fr:link href="/U3L4/" title="Second-order optimality conditions" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/U3L4/" display-uri="U3L4" type="local">second-order conditions</fr:link> disambiguate. Under <fr:link href="/004D/" title="Convex Function" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/004D/" display-uri="004D" type="local">convexity</fr:link> it becomes sufficient as well — a stationary point of a convex function is a global minimizer.</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
