            <fr:title text="Optimality Conditions">Optimality Conditions</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Local conditions that a minimizer of a (not necessarily convex) <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> must satisfy, phrased in terms of its gradient and Hessian at the candidate point. They pin an optimum down to a <fr:link href="/003P/" title="Stationary point" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/003P/" display-uri="003P" type="local">stationary point</fr:link> and then use curvature to separate minima from maxima and saddles.</html:p><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors /><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>27</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/003P/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>003P</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/003P/</fr:route><fr:title text="Stationary point">Stationary point</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>
    A point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x_{\star }}]]></fr:tex> is a stationary point of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f(\cdot )]]></fr:tex>, if <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\nabla  f(\mathbf {x_{\star }})\ =\ \mathbf {0}.]]></fr:tex> Here, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x_{\star }}]]></fr:tex> is also known as a critical point.
  </html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>11</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/I6DT/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>I6DT</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/I6DT/</fr:route><fr:title text="First-order optimality condition">First-order optimality condition</fr:title><fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x_\star }]]></fr:tex> is a local minimizer of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f:\mathbb {R}^n\to \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is continuously differentiable in an open neighborhood of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x_\star }]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x_\star }]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="/003P/" title="Stationary point" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/003P/" display-uri="003P" type="local">stationary point</fr:link>:
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\nabla  f(\mathbf {x_\star })\ =\ \mathbf {0}.]]></fr:tex></html:p><html:p>This is only <html:em>necessary</html:em>: a stationary point may be a maximizer or saddle, which is what the <fr:link href="/U3L4/" title="Second-order optimality conditions" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/U3L4/" display-uri="U3L4" type="local">second-order conditions</fr:link> disambiguate. Under <fr:link href="/004D/" title="Convex Function" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/004D/" display-uri="004D" type="local">convexity</fr:link> it becomes sufficient as well — a stationary point of a convex function is a global minimizer.</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2026</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>11</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/U3L4/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>U3L4</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/U3L4/</fr:route><fr:title text="Second-order optimality conditions">Second-order optimality conditions</fr:title><fr:taxon>Theorem</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f:\mathbb {R}^n\to \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> be twice continuously differentiable in an open neighborhood of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x_\star }]]></fr:tex>.</html:p><html:p><html:strong>Necessary.</html:strong> If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x_\star }]]></fr:tex> is a local minimizer, then
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[(i)\ \nabla  f(\mathbf {x_\star })=\mathbf {0};\qquad  (ii)\ \nabla ^2 f(\mathbf {x_\star })\succeq \mathbf {0}.]]></fr:tex>
That is, it is a <fr:link href="/003P/" title="Stationary point" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/003P/" display-uri="003P" type="local">stationary point</fr:link> whose Hessian is <fr:link href="/003A/" title="Positive (semi)definiteness" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/003A/" display-uri="003A" type="local">positive semidefinite</fr:link>.</html:p><html:p><html:strong>Sufficient.</html:strong> If instead <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\nabla  f(\mathbf {x_\star })=\mathbf {0}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\nabla ^2 f(\mathbf {x_\star })\succ \mathbf {0}]]></fr:tex> (Hessian strictly positive definite), then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x_\star }]]></fr:tex> is a strict local minimizer. The gap between <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\succeq ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\succ ]]></fr:tex> is exactly the ambiguity the <fr:link href="/I6DT/" title="First-order optimality condition" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/I6DT/" display-uri="I6DT" type="local">first-order condition</fr:link> alone cannot resolve.</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 <html:div class="jms-callout" style="
  margin: 1em 0 1em 0.25em;
  padding: 0.5em 1.1em 0.5em 1.2em;
  border-left: 4px solid rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.7);
  border-radius: var(--radius);
  background-color: rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.05);
  "><html:span style="font-weight: 600; color: rgba(90, 90, 110, 0.7);">Remark.</html:span> 
  Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f:\mathbb {R}^{n}\mapsto \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex> be a convex function, then 
  <html:ul><html:li>A local minimizer of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is also its global minimizer. If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is strictly convex, the global minimizer is unique</html:li>
    <html:li>A point is a global minimizer of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> iff <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\mathbf {0}\ \in \ \partial  f(\mathbf {x_{\star }}).]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ul>
  If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\in \mathcal {C}^{1}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\nabla  f(\mathbf {x_{\star }})=\mathbf {0}]]></fr:tex> implies that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbf {x_{\star }}]]></fr:tex> is a global minimizer.
  </html:div>
<fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:contributor><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>7</fr:month><fr:day>6</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/DER4/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>DER4</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/DER4/</fr:route><fr:title text="Constrained Optimality">Constrained Optimality</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>
    Consider a smooth contained problem with <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\min _{\mathbf {x}}f(\mathbf {x}),\quad  \text {s.t.} \quad  r_{i}(\mathbf {x})\ =\ 0,\ 1\leq  i\leq  p,]]></fr:tex> <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[h_{j}(\mathbf {x})\ \leq \ 0,\ 1\leq  j\leq  q.]]></fr:tex> Consider its Lagrangian function <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\mathscr {L}(\mathbf {x},\mathbf {u},\mathbf {v})\ =\ f(\mathbf {x})+\sum _{i=1}^{p}u_{i}\cdot  r_{i}(\mathbf {x})+\sum _{j=1}^{q}v_{j}\cdot  h_{j}(\mathbf {x}).]]></fr:tex>
<fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/kellenkanarios/" title="Kellen Kanarios" uri="https://kellenkanarios.com/kellenkanarios/" display-uri="kellenkanarios" type="local">Kellen Kanarios</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:uri>https://kellenkanarios.com/4IPN/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>4IPN</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/4IPN/</fr:route><fr:title text="KKT Conditions">KKT Conditions</fr:title><fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:ul><html:li>Stationary <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\nabla _{\mathbf {x}}{\mathcal {L}}(\mathbf {x_*},\mathbf {u_*},\mathbf {v_*})\;=\;\mathbf {0}]]></fr:tex></html:li>
   <html:li>Primal Feasibility: <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {array}{l}{{r_{i}(x_{\star })\ =\ 0,\ 1\leq  i\leq  p,}}\\ {{h_{j}(x_{\star })\ \leq \ 0,\ 1\leq  j\leq  q.}}\end {array}]]></fr:tex></html:li>
   <html:li>Dual Feasibility: <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[v_{\star }\geq  0.]]></fr:tex></html:li>
   <html:li>Complimentary slackness: <fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[h_{j}(x_{\star })\cdot  v_{\star  j}\ =\ 0,\quad \forall \ 1\leq  j\leq  q.]]></fr:tex></html:li></html:ul></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter>
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
    </fr:tree>
